Sickle Cell Disease (SCD) advocacy groups, healthcare organizations and other stakeholders in Lagos State have advocated for government partnership with hospitals to monitor pregnant mothers who are at risk of birthing a sickle cell child in all medical centres and help facilitate the screening of newborn for the sickle cell at all hospitals. This formed part of a communiqué issued at the end of a roundtable meeting called by CrimsonBow Sickle Cell Initiative and Project Geneducation High-Level Sickle Cell Advocacy in conjunction with Sickle Cell Foundation Nigeria (SCFN), Sickle Cell Advocacy and Management Initiative (SAMI), TonyMay Foundation (TMF) Sickle Cell Aid and NCD Alliance Nigeria. The roundtable meeting recently held in Lagos and sponsored by the Ford Foundation has as its theme: “Sickle Cell Advocacy: Partnership for Healthcare and Inclusiveness”. According to the organisers of the roundtable meeting, the choice of the theme underscores the lack of adequate healthcare for people living with sickle cell and the discrimination they face in society, most importantly, at schools and workplaces.The meeting called for a policy that would address the inclusion of Sickle Cell Warriors in Health Maintenance organizations (HMO) and workplaces in Nigeria, adding that health insurance inclusion should promote universal health coverage regardless of the genetic disorder or ailment of people are battling with.The meeting advocated for the identification of the children living with sickle cell anaemia early, amplifying prevention through adequate enlightenment campaigns, counselling and testing on genotypes, the establishment of medical centres for sickle care in hospitals by the Ministry of Health, provision of a responsive and inclusive health care system and formation of more informed advocates for Sickle Cell Disease Care as part of the preconditions to archive sustainable management of SCD in the country.Besides, the meeting called on the government to join in the intense advocacy against discrimination against people living with Sickle Cell Disorder, enlightenment by health ministries in schools, religious congregations, community gatherings and so on.The communiqué added, “And there should be a liberal and massive use of print and electronic media in all Nigerian languages for such enlightenment/educative campaigns. Enforcement of the establishment of data registry centres to foster the generation of accurate data of sickle cell patients in Nigeria. “Government should work with general hospitals to help the prompt identification of children with Sickle Cell Disease and that the government should support sickle cell NGOs through collaborations, grants and avenues to obtain funds for projects, among others. On the activities of NGOs, the meeting stated that “Sickle Cell Advocacy Organizations need to be united and start intense advocacy for warriors with an agreed advocacy acronym being formed (With reference to the workaround AIDS, the following was suggested – PCS: Prevent it, Catch it early, Supporting a long quality life outcome and healthcare services).“ “More advocacy against discrimination of warriors in schools and workplaces should be done. There is a need for more sensitization at the grassroots level (community leaders, religious leaders, parents and guardians) on sickle cell matters with more emphasis on genotype testing in order to limit the number of children born with Sickle Cell Disease. The communiqué added, “Pharmaceutical companies need to give out and support the NGOs, collaborations between pharmaceutical companies and other healthcare providers.“People living with SCD are to eat and stay healthy to reduce chances of crisis, warriors are expected to give support and care to other warriors and they should also advocate for themselves and encourage the NGOs,” the communiqué stated.